---
import LocationLayout from '../../layouts/LocationLayout.astro';
import { marsLocations } from '../../data/marsLocations';

const location = marsLocations.find(loc => loc.id === 'gusev-crater');
if (!location) {
  throw new Error('Gusev Crater location not found');
}
---

<LocationLayout title="Gusev Crater - Mars Location" location={location}>
  <!-- Hero Image Section -->
  <div class="mb-8">
    <div
      class="relative h-96 bg-gradient-to-r from-red-800 to-yellow-700 rounded-lg overflow-hidden"
    >
      <div class="absolute inset-0 bg-black/20"></div>
      <div class="absolute bottom-6 left-6 text-white">
        <p class="text-sm opacity-80">
          Spirit rover's panoramic view of Columbia Hills from Gusev Crater
          floor
        </p>
        <p class="text-xs opacity-60">NASA/JPL-Caltech/Cornell</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Overview Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">Overview</h2>
    <div class="grid lg:grid-cols-3 gap-8">
      <div class="lg:col-span-2">
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          Gusev Crater holds a special place in Mars exploration history as the
          landing site of NASA's Spirit rover in 2004. This 160-kilometer-wide
          impact crater was selected because orbital observations suggested it
          once contained a large lake, making it an ideal target for searching
          for evidence of past water activity and potential ancient life.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          Named after Russian astronomer Matvei Gusev, the crater is breached by
          Ma'adim Vallis, a massive outflow channel that appears to have once
          carried enormous floods into the crater. While the main crater floor
          revealed unexpected volcanic rocks instead of lake sediments, the
          nearby Columbia Hills provided compelling evidence of ancient water
          activity.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
          Recent reanalysis of Spirit's data has confirmed that Gusev Crater did
          indeed once hold a lake, validating the original site selection and
          providing new insights into Mars' ancient hydrology and climate.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Quick Facts Sidebar -->
      <div class="bg-gray-800/50 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">Quick Facts</h3>
        <div class="space-y-3">
          <div>
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Diameter:</span>
            <span class="text-white block">160 km</span>
          </div>
          <div>
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Location:</span>
            <span class="text-white block">14.6°S 175.5°E</span>
          </div>
          <div>
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Explorer:</span>
            <span class="text-white block">Spirit Rover (2004-2010)</span>
          </div>
          <div>
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Mission Duration:</span>
            <span class="text-white block">6+ years (planned: 90 days)</span>
          </div>
          <div>
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Key Discovery:</span>
            <span class="text-white block">Ancient lake confirmation</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Spirit Mission Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Spirit's Epic Journey
    </h2>
    <div
      class="bg-gradient-to-br from-red-900/30 to-orange-800/20 p-8 rounded-lg border border-red-700/50"
    >
      <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        Spirit's mission at Gusev Crater began on January 4, 2004, with what was
        planned as a 90-day mission but extended to over six years of
        groundbreaking exploration. The rover far exceeded all expectations,
        traveling 7.73 kilometers and making discoveries that revolutionized our
        understanding of Mars' geological and hydrological history.
      </p>

      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-6">
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">
            Landing & Early Exploration
          </h4>
          <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm mb-3">
            Spirit bounced to a landing in the floor of Gusev Crater,
            immediately beginning analysis of the surrounding volcanic rocks and
            beginning the search for water-related minerals.
          </p>
          <ul class="space-y-1 text-gray-300 text-xs">
            <li>• First 90 sols on crater floor</li>
            <li>• Analysis of volcanic basalts</li>
            <li>• Discovery of hematite spherules</li>
            <li>• Evidence of past wind activity</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">
            Columbia Hills Ascent
          </h4>
          <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm mb-3">
            The journey to the Columbia Hills proved pivotal, revealing ancient
            rocks altered by water and providing the strongest evidence for past
            habitability at Gusev.
          </p>
          <ul class="space-y-1 text-gray-300 text-xs">
            <li>• Hydrothermal mineral deposits</li>
            <li>• Silica-rich outcrops</li>
            <li>• Evidence of hot springs</li>
            <li>• Water-altered volcanic rocks</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">
            Final Years & Legacy
          </h4>
          <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm mb-3">
            Spirit's final years were spent conducting detailed studies of
            water-related minerals before becoming trapped in soft soil in 2009
            and eventually falling silent in 2010.
          </p>
          <ul class="space-y-1 text-gray-300 text-xs">
            <li>• Detailed carbonate analysis</li>
            <li>• Seasonal atmospheric studies</li>
            <li>• Long-term climate monitoring</li>
            <li>• Final silent winter 2010</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Columbia Hills Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Columbia Hills: Window to Mars' Past
    </h2>
    <div class="grid lg:grid-cols-3 gap-6">
      <div class="lg:col-span-2">
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          The Columbia Hills, a group of seven hills rising about 300 feet above
          the Gusev crater floor, became the most scientifically rewarding area
          of Spirit's mission. These ancient geological formations, named after
          the crew of Space Shuttle Columbia, preserved a remarkable record of
          water activity on early Mars.
        </p>

        <div class="space-y-4 mb-6">
          <div class="border-l-4 border-blue-500 pl-4">
            <h4 class="font-semibold text-white mb-2">Hydrothermal Activity</h4>
            <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
              Evidence of ancient hot springs similar to those in Yellowstone
              National Park, with silica deposits and mineral assemblages
              indicating high-temperature water activity.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="border-l-4 border-green-500 pl-4">
            <h4 class="font-semibold text-white mb-2">Water-Altered Rocks</h4>
            <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
              Extensive alteration of volcanic rocks by water, creating clay
              minerals and other hydrated phases that required long-term
              water-rock interaction.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="border-l-4 border-orange-500 pl-4">
            <h4 class="font-semibold text-white mb-2">Carbonate Discoveries</h4>
            <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
              The Comanche outcrop revealed magnesium-iron carbonate minerals,
              providing evidence for ancient lake environments and moderate pH
              conditions.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-gray-800/50 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">Hill Names</h3>
        <div class="space-y-2 text-sm">
          <div class="flex justify-between">
            <span class="text-gray-400">Husband Hill:</span>
            <span class="text-white">Highest point</span>
          </div>
          <div class="flex justify-between">
            <span class="text-gray-400">McCool Hill:</span>
            <span class="text-white">Silica deposits</span>
          </div>
          <div class="flex justify-between">
            <span class="text-gray-400">Anderson Hill:</span>
            <span class="text-white">Basaltic rocks</span>
          </div>
          <div class="flex justify-between">
            <span class="text-gray-400">Brown Hill:</span>
            <span class="text-white">Crater rim</span>
          </div>
          <div class="flex justify-between">
            <span class="text-gray-400">Chawla Hill:</span>
            <span class="text-white">Layered rocks</span>
          </div>
          <div class="flex justify-between">
            <span class="text-gray-400">Clark Hill:</span>
            <span class="text-white">Impact breccias</span>
          </div>
          <div class="flex justify-between">
            <span class="text-gray-400">Ramon Hill:</span>
            <span class="text-white">Spirit's final area</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Lake Discovery Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Ancient Lake Confirmation
    </h2>

    <div
      class="bg-gradient-to-br from-blue-900/30 to-blue-800/20 p-8 rounded-lg border border-blue-700/50 mb-8"
    >
      <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">The Lake That Was</h3>
      <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        After years of debate, a 2014 reanalysis of Spirit's data by Arizona
        State University scientist Steve Ruff definitively confirmed that Gusev
        Crater once contained a lake. The evidence came from detailed study of
        the Comanche outcrop in the Columbia Hills, revealing carbonates formed
        by evaporating lake waters rather than hydrothermal processes.
      </p>

      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">
            Formation Process
          </h4>
          <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm mb-3">
            Floodwaters from Ma'adim Vallis entered the crater and ponded,
            creating a shallow lake that repeatedly filled and evaporated,
            concentrating minerals in the sediments.
          </p>
          <ul class="space-y-1 text-gray-300 text-sm">
            <li>• Episodic flooding through breach</li>
            <li>• Lake formation and evaporation cycles</li>
            <li>• Carbonate precipitation from brines</li>
            <li>• Wind erosion of evidence</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">
            Chemical Evidence
          </h4>
          <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm mb-3">
            The carbonate minerals in Comanche show chemical signatures
            consistent with low-temperature surface waters rather than hot
            hydrothermal fluids.
          </p>
          <ul class="space-y-1 text-gray-300 text-sm">
            <li>• Magnesium-iron carbonates</li>
            <li>• Low-temperature formation</li>
            <li>• Evaporite mineral signatures</li>
            <li>• Tephra alteration products</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
        Implications for Habitability
      </h3>
      <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
        The confirmation of an ancient lake at Gusev Crater, combined with
        evidence of hydrothermal activity and moderate pH conditions, suggests
        that this location had multiple potentially habitable environments. The
        diverse water chemistry and long-term stability would have provided
        excellent conditions for any early Martian life forms.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Key Discoveries Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Groundbreaking Discoveries
    </h2>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-8">
      <div
        class="bg-gradient-to-br from-purple-900/50 to-purple-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-purple-700/50"
      >
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
          Hydrothermal Silica
        </h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm mb-4">
          Spirit discovered nearly pure silica deposits at a location dubbed
          "Home Plate," formed by hot water or steam. These deposits are similar
          to those found around hot springs on Earth and represent some of the
          best preservation environments for potential biosignatures.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
          The silica was likely deposited by hot springs or fumaroles, creating
          an environment that on Earth would be teeming with extremophile
          microorganisms.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div
        class="bg-gradient-to-br from-green-900/50 to-green-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-green-700/50"
      >
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
          Hematite Spherules
        </h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm mb-4">
          The discovery of iron oxide spherules ("blueberries") similar to those
          found by Opportunity at Meridiani Planum provided additional evidence
          of water activity, though these formed through different processes at
          Gusev.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
          These spherules form through prolonged water-rock interaction and
          serve as excellent indicators of ancient aqueous environments.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
        Dust Devil Encounters
      </h3>
      <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">
        Spirit encountered numerous dust devils during its mission, including
        some that actually helped clean the rover's solar panels and extend its
        operational life. These encounters provided valuable data about Martian
        atmospheric dynamics and dust transport processes.
      </p>
      <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
        The rover captured dramatic images and videos of dust devils crossing
        the crater floor, contributing to our understanding of Martian
        meteorology and the role of dust in the planet's climate system.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Terraforming Potential Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Terraforming Assessment
    </h2>
    <div
      class="bg-gradient-to-br from-yellow-900/30 to-orange-800/20 p-8 rounded-lg border border-yellow-700/50"
    >
      <div class="flex items-center mb-6">
        <div
          class="w-12 h-12 bg-yellow-600 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center mr-4"
        >
          <span class="text-white font-bold text-xl">7</span>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-white">
            Good Terraforming Potential
          </h3>
          <p class="text-yellow-300">
            Proven habitability with diverse water environments
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">Advantages</h4>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-300 text-sm">
            <li>• Confirmed ancient lake environment</li>
            <li>• Hydrothermal activity evidence</li>
            <li>• Diverse geological features</li>
            <li>• Good solar exposure</li>
            <li>• Natural topographic variety</li>
            <li>• Evidence of stable water chemistry</li>
            <li>• Moderate latitude location</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">Challenges</h4>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-300 text-sm">
            <li>• Limited current water access</li>
            <li>• Dust devil activity</li>
            <li>• Volcanic rock terrain</li>
            <li>• Potential perchlorate contamination</li>
            <li>• Seasonal dust accumulation</li>
            <li>• Limited mineral diversity</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Scientific Legacy Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Scientific Legacy
    </h2>
    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">Mission Impact</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">
          Spirit's mission at Gusev Crater fundamentally changed our
          understanding of Mars' geological and hydrological history. The
          rover's discoveries provided the first definitive proof of
          hydrothermal environments on Mars and confirmed the presence of
          ancient lakes through chemical analysis of mineral deposits.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
          The mission's success led directly to the development of more advanced
          rovers like Curiosity and Perseverance, and established Gusev as a
          model site for understanding Mars' potential for past habitability.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
          Future Exploration Potential
        </h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
          Gusev Crater remains a high-priority target for future Mars
          exploration missions. The diverse geological environments, confirmed
          water activity, and well-characterized terrain make it an ideal
          location for follow-up studies with more advanced instruments,
          particularly for searching for biosignatures in the hydrothermal
          deposits.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- External Resources Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">Learn More</h2>
    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
      <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-4">NASA Resources</h3>
        <ul class="space-y-2">
          <li>
            <a
              href="https://mars.nasa.gov/mer/home/"
              class="text-blue-400 hover:text-blue-300 text-sm"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer"
            >
              Mars Exploration Rovers Mission
            </a>
          </li>
          <li>
            <a
              href="https://www.jpl.nasa.gov/news/spirit-finds-multi-layer-hints-of-past-water-at-mars-gusev-site/"
              class="text-blue-400 hover:text-blue-300 text-sm"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer"
            >
              Spirit's Water Discoveries
            </a>
          </li>
          <li>
            <a
              href="https://mars.nasa.gov/mer/mission/rover/spirit/"
              class="text-blue-400 hover:text-blue-300 text-sm"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer"
            >
              Spirit Rover Details
            </a>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-4">Scientific Papers</h3>
        <ul class="space-y-2">
          <li>
            <a
              href="https://phys.org/news/2014-04-gusev-crater-held-lake-mars.html"
              class="text-blue-400 hover:text-blue-300 text-sm"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer"
            >
              Lake Confirmation Study (2014)
            </a>
          </li>
          <li>
            <a
              href="https://news.asu.edu/content/gusev-crater-once-held-lake-after-all-says-asu-mars-scientist"
              class="text-blue-400 hover:text-blue-300 text-sm"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer"
            >
              ASU Research Analysis
            </a>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</LocationLayout>

